You can generate a table of contents (TOC) automatically in a LaTeX document using the `\tableofcontents` command from the `tocloft` package. Here's a simple example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tocloft}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\section{Methods}
This is the methods section.

\section{Results}
These are the results.

\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion.

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command is placed after the `\begin{document}` command. When you compile this document, LaTeX will automatically generate a table of contents based on the section headings in the document.

If you want to customize the appearance of the TOC, you can use various options provided by the `tocloft` package. For example, to change the font size of the TOC, you can add the following lines in the preamble:

```latex
\setlength{\cftsecfont}{\small}
\setlength{\cftsubsecfont}{\small}
```

This will make the section and subsection headings in the TOC appear in a smaller font size.

Note: You can also use the `titletoc` package, which provides similar functionality to `tocloft`. The syntax is slightly different, but the general idea is the same.

