If this logarithm is an integer, then the number is a power of three, otherwise it's not.

Here is the Java solution:

```java
class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n < 1) {
            return false;
        }
        double log = Math.log(n) / Math.log(3);
        return log == (int) log;
    }
}
```

This solution works because if `n` is a power of three, then the logarithm of `n` to the base 3 will be an integer. If `n` is not a power of three, then the logarithm will not be an integer. The `(int) log` part is used to check if the logarithm is an integer, because in Java, casting a double to an int discards the fractional part. 

Note: This solution works within the given constraints (-231 <= n <= 231 - 1) because the maximum value of n that can be represented by a double in Java is approximately 1.7976931348623157e+308, which is much larger than 2^31 - 1.

